# dawud035bot

A Telegram bot with:
- 🔗 URL shortener (`/shorten <url>`)
- 🖼 Image compression (auto, on photo upload)
- 🔄 Image format conversion (`/convert jpg|png|webp`)

## 1. Create your bot on Telegram

1. Open Telegram, search for **@BotFather**.
2. Send `/newbot`.
3. Choose a display name, then set the username to `dawud035bot`.
4. BotFather gives you a **token** like `123456789:ABCdefGhIJKlmNoPQRstuVWXyz`. Copy it — you'll need it in step 3.

## 2. Push this code to GitHub

```bash
cd dawud035bot
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit - dawud035bot"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/dawud035bot.git
git push -u origin main
```

(Create the empty repo on GitHub first at https://github.com/new — name it `dawud035bot`.)

## 3. Deploy on Railway

1. Go to https://railway.app and log in (GitHub login is easiest).
2. Click **New Project → Deploy from GitHub repo**.
3. Select your `dawud035bot` repo.
4. Once it's created, go to your service → **Variables** tab.
5. Add a variable:
   - Key: `BOT_TOKEN`
   - Value: *(paste the token from BotFather)*
6. Railway will auto-detect the `Procfile` and run `python bot.py` as a **worker** process.
7. Go to **Settings** and make sure the service has a start command matching the Procfile (Railway usually does this automatically).
8. Deploy. Check the **Logs** tab — you should see `Bot started polling...`.

## 4. Test it

Open Telegram, search `@dawud035bot`, hit **Start**, then try:
- `/shorten https://example.com`
- Send any photo
- `/convert png`

## Notes

- This bot uses **polling** (not webhooks), so no public URL/domain is needed — it works out of the box on Railway.
- Never commit your bot token to GitHub. It's read from the `BOT_TOKEN` environment variable set in Railway.
- Free tools used: TinyURL API (link shortening) and Pillow (image conversion/compression) — no paid API keys required.
